Here are the authoritative public test cases for feature9_previous_cycle:
{
  "description": "Move to the previous workspace when the active workspace is the first one on the focused monitor and cycling is enabled. With cycling, instead of creating a new empty workspace behind, navigation wraps around to the last (highest-id) workspace on the focused monitor. Cycling takes precedence over the disable-empty option. When the monitor holds only a single workspace, wrapping returns that same workspace. The direction selector requests the previous workspace.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "current_id": 500,
        "monitor_ids": [
          500,
          502,
          504
        ],
        "occupied_ids": [
          498,
          500,
          502,
          504
        ],
        "previous": true,
        "cycle": true
      },
      "expected_output": "id=504\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "current_id": 500,
        "monitor_ids": [
          500,
          502
        ],
        "occupied_ids": [
          500,
          502
        ],
        "previous": true,
        "cycle": true
      },
      "expected_output": "id=502\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the authoritative public test cases for feature8_previous_no_empty:
{
  "description": "Move to the previous workspace when the active workspace is the first one on the focused monitor but creating empty workspaces behind is disabled. Because no earlier workspace exists on the monitor and the caller has opted out of opening a brand-new empty workspace in that direction, the operation makes no change and returns the active workspace id unchanged. This holds whether the monitor has several workspaces or only the single active one, and regardless of whether other monitors happen to occupy lower ids. The direction selector requests the previous workspace.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "current_id": 500,
        "monitor_ids": [
          500,
          502
        ],
        "occupied_ids": [
          500,
          502
        ],
        "previous": true,
        "no_empty_before": true
      },
      "expected_output": "id=500\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "current_id": 500,
        "monitor_ids": [
          500
        ],
        "occupied_ids": [
          500
        ],
        "previous": true,
        "no_empty_before": true
      },
      "expected_output": "id=500\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the authoritative public test cases for feature7_previous_create_empty:
{
  "description": "Move to the previous workspace when the active workspace IS the first one on the focused monitor and creating empty workspaces behind is allowed. In this situation the operation returns the largest workspace id strictly smaller than the active id that is not currently occupied on any monitor. Occupied ids immediately below the active id are skipped one by one until the first free id is found, so a gap between occupied workspaces is filled. The search never goes below the lowest valid workspace id. The direction selector requests the previous workspace.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "current_id": 500,
        "monitor_ids": [
          500,
          501
        ],
        "occupied_ids": [
          500,
          501
        ],
        "previous": true
      },
      "expected_output": "id=499\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "current_id": 3,
        "monitor_ids": [
          3,
          4
        ],
        "occupied_ids": [
          1,
          3,
          4
        ],
        "previous": true
      },
      "expected_output": "id=2\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the authoritative public test cases for feature6_previous_adjacent_on_monitor:
{
  "description": "Move to the previous workspace when the active workspace is NOT the first one on the focused monitor. The focused monitor exposes the sorted list of workspace ids that live on it; when at least one of those ids is smaller than the active id, the operation selects the immediately preceding id from the monitor's own list. Workspace ids that belong to other monitors and happen to fall numerically between the previous monitor id and the active id are irrelevant and are skipped, because navigation stays within the focused monitor's own ordered set of workspaces. The direction selector requests the previous workspace.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "current_id": 502,
        "monitor_ids": [
          500,
          502
        ],
        "occupied_ids": [
          500,
          502
        ],
        "previous": true
      },
      "expected_output": "id=500\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "current_id": 504,
        "monitor_ids": [
          500,
          504
        ],
        "occupied_ids": [
          500,
          502,
          504
        ],
        "previous": true
      },
      "expected_output": "id=500\n"
    }
  ]
}

